<div class="article article-right">
<div class="hrDotted"></div>
<h4>How can Wave Telecom offer a free service?</h4>
<p>Wave Telecom believes that every website should be fast. Because of Wave Telecom’s technology, we’ve been able to build a CDN that is available to any website online. From the beginning, we worked to minimize the costs of serving every byte. Wherever possible, we use our own custom-built systems that are designed for this purpose. We buy our bandwidth through the wholesale market, which means we\'re paying for the size of our pipe, not for each byte we serve through it. We also peer with other networks wherever possible in order to drive the cost of bandwidth as close to zero as possible. We never charge for bandwidth and are committed to always offering a FREE version of Wave Telecom with at least today’s feature set. Wave Telecom offers additional plans and services which offer even better services at reasonable prices. We hope you love the service and choose to upgrade.</p>
<div class="hrDotted"></div>
</div> 
<div class="article article-right article-rounded">
<h3 class="centered pro-features">Pro features</h3>
<div class="article-3-columns"><h5>Session optimization</h5>
<p>Wave Telecom’s pre-fetching will automatically identify and then optimize the delivery of your most requested resources. Your most popular assets get preloaded into your visitor’s browser so that your second, third and fourth page loads are extra fast.</p></div>
<div class="article-3-columns"><h5>Prioritized requests</h5>
<p>No matter how heavy your server load is, your traffic will never slow down. Wave Telecom prioritizes requests for Pro customers\' websites for maximum performance.</p></div>
<div class="article-3-columns article-3-columns-last"><h5>SPDY</h5>
<p>SPDY is a new protocol that removes the bottlenecks of HTTP. You can support SPDY without having to make any changes to your origin server. Visitors with browsers that support SPDY connect to Wave Telecom over the protocol. Wave Telecom handles the multiplexing and begins sending down objects that we have in cache. The request to the origin server for non-cached objects is sent over standard HTTP/S. Get SPDY support with a single click.</p></div>
